NEW YORK – Rapper and businessman Jay-Z  sat down with New York Times executive editor Dean Baquet to discuss a variety of topics, including music and being black in America under President Donald Trump. The musician earlier in 2017 release his 13th studio album 4:44, a soul-baring album on love, life and social fractures. In his interview with the editor, the Brooklyn rapper explored topics ranging from that album to racism, wealth, intelligence, OJ Simpson, his mother’s sexuality and his relationship with protégé Kanye West. eNCA